	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_65013279">&ldquo;Analysts&rdquo; claim they&rsquo;ve matched Japanese quality? What analyst, exactly? Maybe it&rsquo;s true, but maybe it&rsquo;s not. My money would be on &ldquo;not&rdquo;.

<br> <br>
Their battery tech is better? That&rsquo;s a tall claim. Gonna need real proof. A slick website and a pdf spec sheet won&rsquo;t convince me.
<br> <br>
If I buy a Toyota, I can reasonably expect 150-200k miles over a solid 15 years or more. I know the warranty will be honored. If I need replacement parts, the car shop down the street can order them and get them the next day. I know that any safety issues will be addressed by a recall. The Chinese auto industry has a history of iterating models super fast. That&rsquo;s great but they abandon previous model to the trash heap. Your $18,000 EV isn&rsquo;t a good deal if it breaks in year 3, the company won&rsquo;t return your calls and no shop can get replacement parts.

<br> <br>
Sure, it&rsquo;s possible, maybe China managed to replicate and surpass the 50 years that Japan invested into polishing their cars to today&rsquo;s level of near-perfection, and it only took them 5-10 years to do it. Eyeroll.</div>
	</div>

